= Abstract

This dissertation presents the design and implementation of Nyx, a full-stack astronomical observation platform that integrates data from NASA's Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite (TESS) with ground-based observations captured from Mauritius. The backend is implemented in C++23 using the Drogon HTTP framework and follows a clean architecture with strict layer separation. A four-stage data ingestion pipeline queries the MAST API for target resolution and TESS observation metadata, discovers FITS data products, downloads binary light curve files, and parses them using CFITSIO into structured time-series records stored in PostgreSQL. The authentication system supports local registration with email verification and Google OAuth2, using JWT access tokens with refresh token rotation and reuse detection. The frontend, built with Next.js and Plotly.js, provides interactive light curve visualisation with WebGL rendering and supports overlay of ground-based observations on TESS data. The system exposes 25 REST API endpoints across five domains and is validated with 136 unit tests using GoogleTest. Data validation against the known exoplanet host star pi Mensae confirms that the ingested TESS light curves are consistent with published transit parameters. The platform addresses a gap in existing tools by providing a single interface for target resolution, space-based data retrieval, ground-based observation management, and cross-source data comparison.
